Digital Computation of the Fractional Fourier Transform (1996)

The FrFT has been widely used in a lot of fields, especially in communications. However, the operations with respect to the continuous domain can lead to considerable computational complexity. To mitigate this issue, several papers have considered the proposal of discrete FrFT (DFrFT). To start with, we simply provide the sampling-based form.

Sampling-based DFrFT

There are three primary papers delving into this topic.

  • Kraniauskas directly sampled the time and fractional Fourier domain.
  • Ozaktas derived the efficient and accurate DFrFT.(prevalent)
  • Pei defined another DFrFT form.(prevalent)

  • Q - Algorithms for resolving the coefficients of polynomial phase of non-linear chirps

  • A1 - ESPRIT for Polynomial-Phase Signals (PP-ESPRIT)

    Idea. Successive finite differencing of a polynomial-phase signal turns it into a cisoid with a Vandermonde structure; then apply ESPRIT to get coefficients in closed form.

    Sketch for a second-order chirp

    1. First difference: .
    2. Form a Hankel/Toeplitz data matrix from Î”x[n]\Delta x[n], compute its signal subspace (SVD).
    3. Apply ESPRIT shift-invariance to obtain the cisoid â€œfrequencyâ€. Its slope across yields , and the intercept gives .
    4. Estimate by LS on with known .

    Pros. Super-resolution, no grid search, excellent for short data records.

    Cons. Needs decent SNR and careful model order (typically 1).

  • A2 - Phase Unwrapping + Weighted Least Squares (WLS)

    Idea. Unwrap the instantaneous phase and fit a quadratic directly.

    1. Compute and unwrap.
    2. Solve

    with robust weights (e.g., Tukey/Huber).

    1. Closed-form via normal equations or QR.

    Pros. Analytic, fast, no transforms.

    Cons. Needs good SNR/initialization; use smoothing or short-time averaging before unwrapping.

  • A3 - Fractional Fourier Transform (FrFT) Ridge Maximization

    Idea. A linear FM becomes a tone after a rotation of the time-frequency plane; maximize concentration to read off Î±\alpha.

    1. Sweep FrFT order aa (rotation ) and find that maximizes spectral sharpness (e.g., kurtosis/peakness) of .
    2. Convert aâ‹†a^\star to chirp rate Î±\alpha via the FrFT convention you use (the formula depends on your normalization).
    3. De-chirp and estimate as in #1.

    Pros. Very intuitive and robust for broad-band chirps.

    Cons. Be meticulous about FrFT normalization to map Î¸\theta to Î±\alpha correctly.

  • A4 - Radon/Ambiguity-Domain Hough Methods (RAT/Radon-TFD)
